From Chicago, Asbell began his professional career performing and recording  with many of the blues greats, including John Lee Hooker, Otis Rush, and Magic Sam.  In 1971, Asbell moved to Vermont as part of the "back to the land" movement, and he remains based in Vermont.  Asbell expanded his performance and recording to jazz musicians (e.g., James Carter, Joshua Redman, Betty Carter)  and folk musicians (e.g., Rosalie Sorrells, David Bromberg, Mary McCaslin).  In 1978, he formed the jazz/fusion band Kilimanjaro.  Asbell as taught guitar privately and at colleges, and he is currently associated with the University of Vermont and Middlebury College.

name: Therese Giehse
comments: Actress born in Munich to German-Jewish parents. She first performed on stage in 1920. She became a major star in the theater, in films and in political cabaret. In the late 1920s through 1933 she was a leading actress at the famous "Münchner Kammerspiele". When the Nazis came to power in 1933 Giehse left Germany for Zürich, where she continued to perform in exile playing leading roles in Zürich including in Erika Mann's acclaimed political cabaret "Die Pfeffermühle". She played the first Mother Courage in the world premiere of Bertolt Brecht's Mutter Courage und ihre Kinder in 1941 at the Schauspielhaus in Zürich.

name: Kurt Tucholsky
comments: Journalist, satirist and writer born in Berlin-Moabit. He was one of the most important journalists of the Weimar Republic. He saw himself as a left-wing democrat and pacifist and warned against anti-democratic tendencies and the threat of National Socialism. His fears were confirmed when the Nazis came to power in 1933: his books were listed on the Nazis' censorship as "Entartete Kunst" (Degenerate art) and burned and he lost his German citizenship. He died in Gothenburg, Sweden from an overdose of sleeping tablets.

name: Wild Man Fischer
comments: Fischer was institutionalized at age 16 and diagnosed with paranoid schizophrenia and bipolar disease.  After escaping from the mental institution, Fischer lived on the streets of Los Angeles, selling passersby a cappella versions of his songs for a dime. Frank Zappa heard Fischer singing on the streets and was responsible for the production and release of his first album.  Due to his mental problems, Fischer had difficulty maintaining relationships.  After an extended paranoid episode in 2003, Fischer became a resident of an assisted living facility for mental patients, where he lived until his death.
